\begin_inset Formula $m_{jk}=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ik}=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Steps:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Find 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(M_{R}\right)_{\bigodot}^{2}$
\end_inset

 (the cartesian product.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}\times M_{R}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ik}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(M_{R}\right)_{\bigodot}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, then same thing should happen in
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
To understand why (source: 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Matrix transitivity - Stackexchange"
target "https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/228898/how-to-check-whether-a-relation-is-transitive-from-the-matrix-representation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
First note that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

 tells you how many 'one-step paths' in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

 that are in the relation set 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
So for example, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{R}=\begin{bmatrix}0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

 shows that we have 3 'one-step' paths, which are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(1,2\right),\left(2,2\right),\left(2,3\right)\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
So by multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

, we are finding how many '2-step' paths in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

, so we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(M_{R}^{2}\right)_{\odot} & =\begin{bmatrix}\boldsymbol{0} & \boldsymbol{1} & \boldsymbol{0}\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}\odot\begin{bmatrix}0 & \boldsymbol{1} & 0\\
0 & \boldsymbol{1} & 0\\
0 & \boldsymbol{1} & 0
\end{bmatrix}\\
\left(M_{R}^{2}\right)_{\odot} & =\begin{bmatrix}0 & \boldsymbol{1} & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If you didn't notice, lets look at the first row and column in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

, in the 2nd cell inside 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(M_{R}^{2}\right)_{\odot}$
\end_inset

we multiplied the matrix coordinates as per follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{ij}*m_{jk}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Essentially, we did
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
m_{00}*m_{10}+m_{10}*m_{11}+m_{20}*m_{12} & =\left(0,0\right)*\left(1,0\right)+\left(1,0\right)*\left(1,1\right)+\left(2,0\right)*\left(1,2\right)\\
 & =\left(0*1\right)+\left(1*1\right)+\left(0*1\right)\\
 & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
So, if we have a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in a column inside 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, then that means there are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at least
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a 2-link that involves 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ij}*m_{jk}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, that column, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ik}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

 must also have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at least
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a 1-link, to satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ik}=m_{ij}*m_{jk}$
\end_inset

 and be 
\series bold
transitive
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In many cases, we only write 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 even if there are more links in same cell.
 This is because additional links does not concern us as we only want to
 know if it satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{ik}=m_{ij}*m_{jk}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
